{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}
The '''2016 Southeast Asian haze''' is an [[air pollution]] crisis affecting several countries in [[Southeast Asia]], including [[Indonesia]], [[Malaysia]] and [[Singapore]].<ref name=BBC1>{{cite web|title=The haze is back across South East Asia|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-37192800|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=CNBC1>{{cite web|last1=Tan|first1=Huileng|title=Singapore air quality worsens overnight as Indonesia fire arrests jump|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2016/08/25/haze-news-singapore-air-quality-worsens-overnight-as-indonesia-fire-arrests-jump.html|publisher=[[CNBC]]|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref>
The haze is caused by Indonesian agricultural fires in [[Sumatra]] and [[Kalimantan]].<ref name=BBC1/> The fires are attributed to illegal [[slash-and-burn]] practices by companies and individual farmers, which remove vegetation to make way for plantations of [[palm oil]], pulp and paper.<ref name=BBC1/><ref name=CNBC1/><ref name=Reuters1>{{cite web|last1=Zaharia|first1=Marius|title=Smoke from Indonesian fires hits 'unhealthy' level in Singapore|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-indonesia-haze-idUKKCN1110L4|publisher=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref>
On 17 August, 365 hot spots were detected on Indonesia's Sumatra island, with 278 in the province of [[Riau]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Satellites Detect 365 Hotspots Across Sumatra|url=http://en.tempo.co/read/news/2016/08/18/206796797/Satellites-Detect-365-Hotspots-Across-Sumatra|work=[[Tempo (Indonesian magazine)|Tempo]]|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref> On 18 August, 158 hot spots were detected in the province of [[West Kalimantan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Haze is heading Singapore’s way, Indonesia warns|url=http://www.todayonline.com/world/asia/indonesia-haze-warning-fires-flare|work=[[Today (Singapore newspaper)|Today]]|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref> By 26 August, six Indonesian provinces had declared a [[state of emergency]] due to the fires: [[Central Kalimantan]], [[Jambi]], Riau, [[South Kalimantan]], [[South Sumatra]] and West Kalimantan.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Endi|first1=Severianus|title=Residents’ health at risk as haze lingers in W. Kalimantan|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2016/08/25/residents-health-risk-haze-lingers-w-kalimantan.html|work=[[The Jakarta Post]]|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref> Indonesia has reported arresting around 450 people in 2016 for their connections with the fires.<ref name=BBC1/><ref name=CNBC1/>
On 17 August 2016, Malaysia's Air Pollutant Index first surpassed the 'unhealthy' level of 100 for the region's dry season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Haze briefly crosses into unhealthy range in M’sia|url=http://www.todayonline.com/world/haze-levels-increasing-across-malaysia|work=[[Today (Singapore newspaper)|Today]]|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref> On 24 August, Malaysia offered to dispatch two [[Bombardier 415]] fire-fighting aircraft if Indonesia would officially request help to tackle the fires.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Goh|first1=Melissa|title=Malaysia offers Indonesia assistance to fight haze: Minister|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asiapacific/malaysia-offers-indonesia/3075754.html|publisher=[[Channel News Asia]]|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref>
In June 2016, Singapore offered Indonesia a [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules]] aircraft for [[cloud seeding]], as well as a [[Singapore Civil Defence Force]] fire-fighting team, and assistance in providing satellite pictures and determining the coordinates of fires.<ref>{{cite web|title=Singapore offers help to Indonesia to fight fires and haze as dry season starts|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapore-offers-help-to-indonesia-to-fight-fires-and-haze-as-dry-season-starts|publisher=[[The Straits Times]]|accessdate=26 August 2016|last1=Chew|first1=Hui Min}}</ref> On 26 August 2016, Singapore's 24-hour Pollutant Standards Index (PSI) entered the 'unhealthy' range of above 100, while its 3-hour PSI reached 215.<ref name=BBC1/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Md Noh|first1=Nurulnadiah|last2=Tan|first2=Audrey|title=Haze update: PSI for next 24 hours forecast to be in unhealthy range, says NEA|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/environment/haze-back-in-singapore-24-hour-psi-reaches-moderate-level|publisher=[[The Straits Times]]|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref>
