{{Infobox dam | name = Baogang Tailings Dam | name_official = | image = | image_size = | image_caption = | image_alt = | location_map = China | location_map_size = | location_map_caption = | location_map_alt = | coordinates = {{coord|40|38|16.3|N|109|41|16.7|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | country = | location = [[Baotou]] | purpose = | status = | construction_began = 1955 | opening = 1965 | demolished = | cost = | owner = [[Baotou Steel]] | dam_type = Embankment, tailings | dam_crosses = | dam_length = {{Convert|11.5|km|mi|abbr=on}} | dam_height = {{Convert|6|m|ft|abbr=on}} | dam_height_foundation= | dam_height_thalweg = | dam_elevation_crest = {{Convert|1045|m|ft|abbr=on}} | dam_width_crest = | dam_width_base = | dam_volume = | spillway_count = | spillway_type = | spillway_capacity = | res_name = | res_capacity_total = {{Convert|85000000|m3|acre.ft|abbr=on}} | res_capacity_active = {{Convert|68800000|m3|acre.ft|abbr=on}} | res_capacity_inactive= | res_catchment = | res_surface = {{Convert|10|km2|mi2|abbr=on}} | res_max_length = | res_max_width = | res_max_depth = | res_elevation = | res_tidal_range = | plant_name = | plant_coordinates = | plant_operator = | plant_commission = | plant_decommission = | plant_type = | plant_turbines = | plant_hydraulic_head = | plant_capacity = | plant_annual_gen = | website = | extra = }} '''Baogang Tailings Dam''', also known as the '''Baotou Tailings Dam''' or '''Weikuang Dam''', is a [[tailings dam]] in [[Inner Mongolia]], [[China]], on the outer ring of the city of [[Baotou]], about 20 kilometres from the city centre. The dam is filled with [[tailings]] and waste slurry from nearby [[rare earth mineral]] refinery plants. Accounts of the tailings dam appeared in western media outlets after a visit in 2015 by British writers Tim Maughan, Liam Young and Kate Davies from ''Unknown Fields'', a "nomadic design studio" from London.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Maughan|first1=Tim|title=The dystopian lake filled by the world´s tech lust|url=http://www.bbc.com/future/story/20150402-the-worst-place-on-earth|publisher=BBC|accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ryan|first1=Rowena|title=Baotou is the world’s biggest supplier of rare earth minerals and it’s hell on Earth|url=https://www.news.com.au/travel/world-travel/asia/baotou-is-the-worlds-biggest-supplier-of-rare-earth-minerals-and-its-hell-on-earth/news-story/371376b9893492cfc77d23744ca12bc5|publisher=news.com.au|accessdate=5 October 2018}}</ref> This account contrasts with the Chinese media's own reporting of the rare earth industry in the area.<ref>{{cite web|last1= Meng|first1=Fanbin|title=Huge rare earth industrial park coming to Inner Mongolia|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/business/2017-08/29/content_31257475.htm|publisher=China Daily|accessdate=5 October 2018}}</ref>
Construction of the dam began in 1955 and it was complete in 1963 but was not used until 1965. It is owned by [[Baotou Steel]]. The circular dam is {{Convert|11.5|km|mi|abbr=on}} long and has a {{Convert|85000000|m3|acre.ft|abbr=on}} capacity. The dam will eventually increase {{Convert|1045|m|ft|abbr=on}} in height and have a capacity of {{Convert|233800000|m3|acre.ft|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Baotou Steel Group tailings line monitoring system |url=http://www.beijinghuace.com/modetail.aspx?PID=200&classid=80 |publisher=Beijing China test-chi Technology Co., Ltd. |accessdate=8 January 2016 |language=Chinese |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160121022641/http://beijinghuace.com/modetail.aspx?PID=200&classid=80 |archivedate=21 January 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Capilla|first1=Antonio Valero|last2=Delgado|first2=Alicia Valero|title=Thanatia: The Destiny of the Earth's Mineral Resources: A Thermodynamic Cradle-to-Cradle Assessment|publisher=World Scientific|isbn=9814602493|page=243|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EVUCCwAAQBAJ&dq=baotou+tailings+dam+height+meters&source=gbs_navlinks_s}}</ref>
[[Bayan Obo Mining District]], about 120 kilometres from Baotou city is the world's biggest supplier of rare earth minerals. They are used in the production of smartphones, tablets and other technology, like wind turbines. Production creates millions of tons of waste per year which has drawn much criticism of the dam.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Breslin|first1=Sean|title=Toxic Lake in Inner Mongolia Created By World's Addiction To High-Tech Gadgets|url=http://www.weather.com/science/environment/news/baotou-artificial-lake-toxic-sludge|website=Weather.com|accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> Chemicals in the dam have been linked to lower crop yields in surrounding farmlands and serious health problems among local villagers.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kiggins|first1=Ryan David|title=The Political Economy of Rare Earth Elements: Rising Powers and Technological Change|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=9781137364258|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=waGhCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT127&lpg=PT127&dq=baotou+tailings+dam+height+meters&source=bl&ots=YuRTsRuDRF&sig=fbNI6qUVt--0uFhXcZkQ4wA0Jnk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwimg--G-5jKAhVE8mMKHfncAJkQ6AEIODAE#v=onepage&q=baotou%20tailings%20dam%20height%20meters&f=false}}</ref>
