[[Category:History of the United States Navy]] [[Category:United States military in Japan]] [[Category:Buildings and structures in Kanagawa Prefecture]] [[Category:Japan–United States relations]] [[Category:Japanese law]] [[Category:Pollution in Japan]] [[Category:Incinerators]] [[Category:Environmental disasters in Japan]]

The {{nihongo|'''Kokuba River'''|国場川|Kokubagawa}} is a river in [[Naha, Okinawa]], and is the hydrographic resource for domestic urban fresh water.  A number of geographical places on Okinawa bear its name, such as {{nihongo|Lake Man Park|漫湖公園}} and {{nihongo|Kokuba Danchi|国場団地}}.  The river flows into the [[East China Sea]].

==Poisoning==
The river and people living around it suffered when [[pentachlorophenol]] herbicides were dumped into the river, obtained from the U.S. military by a civilian company in 1971, when it was still a [[Territories of the United States#Classification of former U.S. territories and administered areas|US territory]].   Some 30,000 Okinawans had used the river for water supply, which was halted when school children came down with abdominal pain and nausea.<ref name="jtjunk">{{cite-web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/community/2013/11/11/issues/okinawa-the-junk-heap-of-the-pacific/#.U8uF0rRX_9k|title=Okinawa: the junk heap of the Pacific|publisher=The Japan Times}}</ref>  Okinawa continues to suffer from extremely elevated levels of [[dioxin]]s far beyond allowed limits, from the areas in and surrounding its US military bases, which are adjacent urban population centers, despite decades of denials and cleanup refusals by US officials.<ref name="jtjunk"/>

