The {{nihongo|'''Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster'''|福島第一原子力発電所事故|[[Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant|Fukushima Dai-ichi]] ''({{Audio|Fukushima daiichi.ogg|pronunciation|lang=ja|help=no}})'' genshiryoku hatsudensho jiko}} was a series of [[Nuclear and radiation accidents#Equipment failure|equipment failures]], [[nuclear meltdown]]s, and [[Nuclear and radiation accidents#Radiation accidents|releases of radioactive materials]] at the [[Fukushima I Nuclear Power Plant]], following the [[2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami|Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami]] on 11 March 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=10716671|title=Japan's unfolding disaster 'bigger than Chernobyl'|work=[[New Zealand Herald]]|date=2 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Explainer: What went wrong in Japan's nuclear reactors |url=http://spectrum.ieee.org/tech-talk/energy/nuclear/explainer-what-went-wrong-in-japans-nuclear-reactors |work=IEEE Spectrum |date=4 April 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zujk3oQL?url=http://spectrum.ieee.org/tech-talk/energy/nuclear/explainer-what-went-wrong-in-japans-nuclear-reactors |archivedate=4 July 2011 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref> It is the largest nuclear disaster since the [[Chernobyl disaster]] of 1986.<ref>[http://in.ibtimes.com/articles/132391/20110409/japan-nuclear-crisis-radiation.htm "Analysis: A month on, Japan nuclear crisis still scarring"] {{webarchive |url=https://www.webcitation.org/5y2agYEQZ?url=http://in.ibtimes.com/articles/132391/20110409/japan-nuclear-crisis-radiation.htm |date=18 April 2011 }} ''International Business Times'' (Australia). 9 April 2011, retrieved 12 April 2011; excerpt, According to [[James M. Acton|James Acton]], Associate of the Nuclear Policy Program at the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, "Fukushima is not the worst nuclear accident ever but it is the most complicated and the most dramatic...This was a crisis that played out in real time on TV. Chernobyl did not."</ref>

The plant comprises six separate [[boiling water reactor]]s originally designed by [[General Electric]] (GE), and maintained by the [[Tokyo Electric Power Company]] (TEPCO). At the time of the quake, Reactor 4 had been de-fueled while 5 and 6 were in cold [[shutdown (nuclear reactor)|shutdown]] for planned maintenance.<ref>{{cite news|author=Black, Richard |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-12745186 |title=Reactor breach worsens prospects |work=BBC Online |date=15 March 2011 |accessdate=23 March 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5xDYTkU7P?url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-12745186 |archivedate=16 March 2011 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref> Immediately after the earthquake, the remaining reactors 1-3 shut down automatically, and emergency generators came online to control electronics and coolant systems. However, the tsunami following the earthquake quickly flooded the low-lying rooms in which the emergency generators were housed. The flooded generators failed, cutting power to the critical pumps that must continuously circulate [[Nuclear reactor coolant#Water|coolant water]] through a nuclear reactor for several days in order to keep it from melting down after being shut down. As the pumps stopped, the [[Decay heat#Power reactors in shutdown|reactors overheated]] due to the normal high radioactive [[decay heat]] produced in the first few days after nuclear reactor shutdown (smaller amounts of this heat normally continue to be released for years, but are not enough to cause fuel melting).

At this point, only prompt flooding of the reactors with seawater could have cooled the reactors quickly enough to prevent meltdown. Salt water flooding was delayed because it would ruin the costly reactors permanently. Flooding with seawater was finally commenced only after the government ordered that seawater be used, and at this point it was already too late to prevent meltdown.<ref>F. Tanabe, Journal of Nuclear Science and Technology, 2011, volume 48, issue 8, pages 1135 to 1139</ref>

As the water boiled away in the reactors and the water levels in the [[Spent nuclear fuel|fuel]] rod pools dropped, the reactor fuel rods began to overheat severely, and to melt down. In the hours and days that followed, Reactors 1, 2 and 3 experienced full [[Nuclear meltdown|meltdown]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/asiapcf/06/06/japan.nuclear.meltdown/index.html?iref=NS1 |title=3 nuclear reactors melted down after quake, Japan confirms |work=CNN|date= 7 June 2011|accessdate=13 July 2011| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140414115531/http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/asiapcf/06/06/japan.nuclear.meltdown/index.html?iref=NS1 | archivedate = 2014-04-14| deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/T110607005367.htm |title='Melt-through' at Fukushima? / Govt report to IAEA suggests situation worse than meltdown |work=Yomiuri |date=8 June 2011 |accessdate=8 June 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zSkWxIIC?url=http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/T110607005367.htm |archivedate=15 June 2011 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy }}</ref>

In the intense heat and pressure of the melting reactors, a reaction between the nuclear fuel metal cladding and the remaining water surrounding them produced explosive hydrogen gas. As workers struggled to cool and shut down the reactors, several [[hydrogen explosion|hydrogen-air]] chemical explosions occurred.<ref name="IAEA15March"/><ref>[http://www.hyer.eu/news/regional-news/hydrogen-in-nuclear-accidents-what-is-the-role-of-the-gas-in-fukushima Hydrogen explosions Fukushima nuclear plant: what happened?] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202235552/http://www.hyer.eu/news/regional-news/hydrogen-in-nuclear-accidents-what-is-the-role-of-the-gas-in-fukushima |date=2 December 2013 }}</ref>

Concerns about the repeated small explosions, the atmospheric venting of radioactive gasses, and the possibility of larger explosions led to a {{convert|20|km|mi|abbr=on}}-radius evacuation around the plant. During the early days of the accident workers were temporarily evacuated at various times for [[radiation]] safety reasons. At the same time, sea water that had been exposed to the melting rods was returned to the sea heated and radioactive in large volumes for several months until recirculating units could be put in place to repeatedly cool and re-use a limited quantity of water for cooling. The earthquake damage and flooding in the wake of the tsunami hindered external assistance. Electrical power was slowly restored for some of the reactors, allowing for automated cooling.<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704021504576210251376606080 Stricken reactors may get power Sunday], ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', 19 March 2011 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510123846/http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748704021504576210251376606080.html |date=10 May 2013 }}</ref>

Japanese officials initially assessed the accident as Level 4 on the [[International Nuclear Event Scale]] (INES) despite the views of other international agencies that it should be higher. The level was later raised to 5 and eventually to 7, the maximum scale value.<ref>Justin McCurry. [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/apr/12/japan-nuclear-alert-level-seven Japan raises nuclear alert level to seven]. The Guardian. 12 April 2011 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130311011101/http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2011/apr/12/japan-nuclear-alert-level-seven |date=11 March 2013 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1375981/Now-radiation-Japan-bad-Chernobyl-crisis-level-raised-seven-second-time-history.html 'Now radiation in Japan is as bad as radiation level is raised to 7 for only the second time in history'] ''Daily Mail'' 12 April 2011.</ref> The Japanese government and TEPCO have been criticized in the foreign press for poor communication with the public and improvised cleanup efforts.<ref>{{cite news |author=Wagner, Wieland |title=Problematic public relations: Japanese leaders leave people in the dark |work=Der Spiegel |date=15 March 2011 |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/0,1518,751109,00.html |accessdate=19 March 2011| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110415211011/http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/0,1518,751109,00.html | archivedate = 2011-04-15| deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=China urges Japan's openness amid panic buying of salt |work=Channel NewsAsia |date=17 March 2011 |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/afp_asiapacific/view/1117111/1/.html |accessdate=17 March 2011|agency = Agence France-Presse}}</ref><ref name="Hackenbroch"/> On 20 March, the [[Chief Cabinet Secretary]] [[Yukio Edano]] announced that the plant would be decommissioned once the crisis was over.

The Japanese government estimates the total amount of radioactivity released into the atmosphere was approximately one-tenth as much as was released during the Chernobyl disaster.<ref name="Frank N. von Hippel 27–36"/> Significant amounts of radioactive material have also been released into ground and ocean waters. Measurements taken by the Japanese government 30–50&nbsp;km from the plant showed [[caesium-137]] levels high enough to cause concern,<ref name="NewScie2"/> leading the government to ban the sale of food grown in the area. Tokyo officials temporarily recommended that tap water should not be used to prepare food for infants.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/19/us-japan-nuclear-food-idUSTRE72I1X120110319 Japan mulls Fukushima food ban: IAEA], Reuters, 19 March 2011 {{webarchive |url=https://www.webcitation.org/5xJGKu1SX?url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/19/us-japan-nuclear-food-idUSTRE72I1X120110319 |date=19 March 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Justin McCurry in Osaka |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/mar/23/tokyo-water-unsafe-infants |title=Tokyo water unsafe for infants after high radiation levels detected |date=23 March 2010 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=23 March 2011 |place=London| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110408054717/http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2011/mar/23/tokyo-water-unsafe-infants | archivedate = 2011-04-08| deadurl=no}}</ref> In May 2012, TEPCO reported that at least 900 [[Petabecquerel|PBq]] had been released "into the atmosphere in March last year [2011] alone" although it has been said staff may have been told to lie, and give false readings to try and cover up true levels of radiation.<ref name="english.kyodonews.jp">{{cite web|url=http://english.kyodonews.jp/news/2012/05/159960.html|title=TEPCO puts radiation release early in Fukushima crisis at 900 PBq|work=[[Kyodo News]]|date=24 May 2012|accessdate=24 May 2012| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120524191342/http://english.kyodonews.jp/news/2012/05/159960.html | archivedate = 2012-05-24| deadurl=yes}}</ref><ref name="Kevin Krolicki">{{cite news|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2012/05/24/nuclear-japan-radiation-fukushima-idINDEE84N0CR20120524|title=Fukushima radiation higher than first estimated|work=[[Reuters]]|author=Kevin Krolicki|date=24 May 2012|accessdate=24 May 2012| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131015040840/http://in.reuters.com/article/2012/05/24/nuclear-japan-radiation-fukushima-idINDEE84N0CR20120524 | archivedate = 2013-10-15| deadurl=no}}</ref>

A few of the plant's workers were severely injured or killed by the disaster conditions resulting from the earthquake. There were no immediate deaths due to direct radiation exposures, but at least six workers have exceeded lifetime legal limits for radiation and more than 300 have received significant radiation doses. Predicted future cancer deaths due to accumulated radiation exposures in the population living near Fukushima have ranged from none<ref>{{cite news|agency=NPR|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/transcript/transcript.php?storyId=148227596|date=9 March 2012|accessdate=15 April 2012|title=Trauma, Not Radiation, Is Key Concern In Japan| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140309033042/http://www.npr.org/templates/transcript/transcript.php?storyId=148227596 | archivedate = 2014-03-09| deadurl=no}}</ref> to 100<ref name="Caracappa-ANS">{{Citation |last= Caracappa |first= Peter F. |date= 28 June 2011 |title= Fukushima Accident: Radioactive Releases and Potential Dose Consequences |work= ANS Annual Meeting | url= http://www.ans.org/misc/FukushimaSpecialSession-Caracappa.pdf | accessdate=13 September 2011}}</ref> to a non-peer-reviewed "guesstimate"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/ombudsman/2012/03/15/148703963/the-cost-of-fear-the-framing-of-a-fukushima-report|date=15 March 2012|accessdate=15 April 2012|title=The Cost of Fear: The Framing of a Fukushima Report| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140505174012/http://www.npr.org/blogs/ombudsman/2012/03/15/148703963/the-cost-of-fear-the-framing-of-a-fukushima-report | archivedate = 2014-05-05| deadurl=no}}</ref> of 1,000.<ref name="Frank N. von Hippel 27–36"/> On 16 December 2011, Japanese authorities declared the plant to be stable, although it would take decades to decontaminate the surrounding areas and to decommission the plant altogether.<ref>{{cite news|title=Japan PM says Fukushima nuclear site finally stabilised|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-16212057|work=BBC Online|accessdate=7 January 2012|date=16 December 2011| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140220102647/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-16212057 | archivedate = 2014-02-20| deadurl=no}}</ref> On 5 July 2012, the parliament appointed [[#Fukushima_Nuclear_Accident_Independent_Investigation_Commission|The Fukushima Nuclear Accident Independent Investigation Commission]] (NAIIC) submitted its inquiry report to the Japanese parliament,<ref name="National Diet of Japan Fukushima Nuclear Accident Independent Investigation Commission">{{cite web|title=国会事故調 {{!}} 東京電力福島原子力発電所事故調査委員会のホームページ |url=http://naiic.go.jp/en/ |publisher=National Diet of Japan Fukushima Nuclear Accident Independent Investigation Commission |accessdate=9 July 2012 |author=National Diet of Japan Fukushima Nuclear Accident Independent Investigation Commission |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119181123/http://naiic.go.jp/en/ |archivedate=19 January 2013 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy }}</ref> while the government appointed [[#Investigation_Committee_on_the_Accident_at_the_Fukushima_Nuclear_Power_Stations_of_Tokyo_Electric_Power_Company|Investigation Committee on the Accident at the Fukushima Nuclear Power Stations of Tokyo Electric Power Company]] submitted its final report to the Japanese government on 23 July 2012.<ref name="Asahi20120723">{{cite news|title=UPDATE: Government panel blasts lack of 'safety culture' in nuclear accident|url=http://ajw.asahi.com/article/0311disaster/fukushima/AJ201207230081|accessdate=29 July 2012|newspaper=The [[Asahi Shimbun]]|date=23 July 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413220232/http://ajw.asahi.com/article/0311disaster/fukushima/AJ201207230081|archivedate=13 April 2014|deadurl=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Timeline of the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster#Friday.2C 12 October 2012|Tepco admitted for the first time on 12 October 2012]] that it had failed to take stronger measures to prevent disasters for fear of inviting lawsuits or protests against its nuclear plants.<ref name="NYT20121012">{{cite news|last=Fackler |first=Martin |title=Japan Power Company Admits Failings on Plant Precautions |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/13/world/asia/tepco-admits-failure-in-acknowledging-risks-at-nuclear-plant.html?_r=0 |accessdate=13 October 2012 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=12 October 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006070548/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/13/world/asia/tepco-admits-failure-in-acknowledging-risks-at-nuclear-plant.html?_r=0 |archivedate=6 October 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sheldrick|first=Aaron|title=Fukushima operator must learn from mistakes, new adviser says|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2012/10/13/japan-nuclear-adviser-fukushima-idINDEE89C03220121013?feedType=RSS&feedName=worldNews|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=13 October 2012|date=12 October 2012| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140309030940/http://in.reuters.com/article/2012/10/13/japan-nuclear-adviser-fukushima-idINDEE89C03220121013?feedType=RSS&feedName=worldNews | archivedate = 2014-03-09| deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="Yamaguchi20121012">{{cite news|last=Yamaguchi|first=Mari|title=Japan utility agrees nuclear crisis was avoidable|url=http://www.boston.com/news/world/asia/2012/10/12/japan-utility-admits-nuke-crisis-avoidable-says-feared-consequences-new-safety-measures/NK3yENYHgVPQZ76POvbBLL/story.html|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Boston.com|accessdate=13 October 2012|date=12 October 2012| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131005004918/http://www.boston.com/news/world/asia/2012/10/12/japan-utility-admits-nuke-crisis-avoidable-says-feared-consequences-new-safety-measures/NK3yENYHgVPQZ76POvbBLL/story.html | archivedate = 2013-10-05| deadurl=yes}}</ref><ref name="CNN20121012">{{cite web|title=Japanese nuclear plant operator admits playing down risk|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/10/12/world/asia/japan-tepco-report/index.html?hpt=ias_c2|work=CNN Wire Staff|publisher=CNN|accessdate=13 October 2012|date=12 October 2012| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140309032320/http://edition.cnn.com/2012/10/12/world/asia/japan-tepco-report/index.html?hpt=ias_c2 | archivedate = 2014-03-09| deadurl=no}}</ref>

{{TOC limit|3}}

==Unit 1 Reactor==
===Details of the core===

F. Tanabe has estimated that the core contained the following materials:<ref>F. Tanabe, Journal of Nuclear Science and Technology, 2011, vol 48, issue 8, pages 1135 to 1139</ref>
* [[Uranium dioxide]] 78.3 tons
* [[Zirconium]] 32.7 tons
* [[Steel]] 12.5 tons
* [[Boron carbide]] 590 kilograms
* [[Inconel]] 1 ton

===Cooling problems and first radioactivity release===
[[File:Fukushima 1 Nuclear Power Plant 02.jpg|thumb|Unit 1 before the explosion. The joint can be seen between the lower concrete building and upper lighter cladding which was blown away in the explosion.]]
[[File:Fukushima I Unit 1 accident reactor data (en).svg|thumb|Unit 1 water levels and reactor pressures from 11 to 14 March]]

On 11 March at 14:46 JST, in response to the earthquake, TEPCO successfully [[scram]]med the reactor in Unit 1, shutting down all power-producing [[nuclear fission]] [[chain reaction]]s. Evacuated workers reported violent shaking and burst pipes within the reactor building.<ref name="tepco11b">{{cite press release|url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11031103-e.html |title=TEPCO press release 3 |work=Tepco |date=11 March 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yCGtlpb7?url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11031103-e.html |archivedate=25 April 2011 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/T110316005275.htm |title=Terror at N-plant during quake |work=Yomiuri Shimbun |location=Japan |date=17 March 2011 |accessdate=24 April 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ygMQfEn5?url=http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/T110316005275.htm |archivedate=14 May 2011 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy }}</ref> At 15:37, the quake's tsunami inundated the plant and all electrical power to the facility was lost, leaving only emergency batteries. Some of the monitoring and control systems were still operational, though Unit 1's batteries had been damaged by the flood waters. At 15:42, TEPCO declared a "Nuclear Emergency Situation" for Units 1 and 2 because "reactor water coolant injection could not be confirmed for the emergency core cooling systems."<ref name="tepco11b"/> The alert was temporarily cleared when water level monitoring was restored for Unit 1 but it was reinstated at 17:07 JST.<ref name="tepco11b"/> Potentially radioactive steam was released from the primary circuit into the secondary containment area to reduce mounting pressure in the core.<ref>[http://content.usatoday.com/communities/ondeadline/post/2011/03/radiation-1000-times-normal-detected-around-crippled-japanese-plant/1 Radiation 1K times normal at one Japan nuke plant]. ''[[USA Today]]'' (3 January 2011). Retrieved 12 March 2011. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130330071408/http://content.usatoday.com/communities/ondeadline/post/2011/03/radiation-1000-times-normal-detected-around-crippled-japanese-plant/1 |date=30 March 2013 }}</ref>

To cool the reactor, operators resorted to the plant's Emergency core-cooling systems (ECCS), including the [[isolation condenser]]s, and the [[High Pressure Coolant Injection]] systems (HPCI). According to [[NHK]], the isolation condenser system had not been activated in the previous 40 years, and no one present had ever witnessed its operation.<ref>''Meltdown Oversights in the Reactor Cooling System'', NHK World (2013)</ref> It was also later discovered that TEPCO had made changes to the system's original design, without approval or notification of NISA. During the crisis, operators couldn't tell if one of the system's valves was open or closed.<ref name="mainichi1">The Mainichi Shimbun (28 February 2012){{Cite web |url=http://www.houseofjapan.com/local/tepco-ordered-to-report-on-change-in-piping-layout-at-fukushima-plant |title=Archived copy |access-date=19 November 2018 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130629114449/http://www.houseofjapan.com/local/tepco-ordered-to-report-on-change-in-piping-layout-at-fukushima-plant# |archive-date=29 June 2013 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

About 10 minutes after the earthquake, TEPCO operators removed both of Unit 1's isolation condensers from service, and instead activated the HPCI system. At 15:07, the core spray system was activated to cool the suppression pool. Both systems lost power after the tsunami struck the plant.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}} The tsunami's arrival prevented operators from restarting the isolation condensers for more than 30 minutes. Afterwards, they were operated intermittently. Despite being designed to cool Unit 1 for at least 8 hours, the condensers' limited operation did not reduce the heat in the core and containment vessel.

By midnight, water levels in the reactor were falling and TEPCO gave warnings of the possibility of radioactive releases.<ref name="TEPCO12-3:00"/> In the early hours of 12 March, TEPCO reported that radiation levels were rising in the turbine building for Unit 1.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110720010409/http://e.nikkei.com/e/fr/tnks/Nni20110311D11JF351.htm Radiation level rising in Fukushima Nuclear Plant turbine building.] Nikkei.com. 12 March 2011 JST. Retrieved 18:30 GMT 11 March 2011.</ref> Operators were considering venting some of the mounting pressure into the atmosphere, which could result in the release of some radioactivity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asahi.com/national/update/0312/TKY201103110824.html |title=(朝日新聞社)：福島原発炉内蒸気、外に逃す作業検f討　放射能漏れの恐れ – 社会|work=Asahi Shimbun |location=Japan|accessdate=13 March 2011|language=Japanese| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120103171910/http://www.asahi.com/national/update/0312/TKY201103110824.html | archivedate = 2012-01-03| deadurl=yes}}</ref> Later that morning, Chief Cabinet Secretary [[Yukio Edano]] stated that the amount of potential radiation would be small and that the prevailing winds were blowing out to sea.<ref>International Business Times. [http://hken.ibtimes.com/articles/121928/20110312/japan-quake.htm Japan warns of small radiation leak from quake-hit plant] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120715062844/http://hken.ibtimes.com/articles/121928/20110312/japan-quake.htm |date=15 July 2012 }} Retrieved 11 March 2011, 21:48 (GMT)</ref> Pressure inside Unit 1 continued to rise.<ref name="WNN">{{cite news|title=Massive earthquake hits Japan |url=http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/RS_Massive_earthquake_hits_Japan_1103111.html |accessdate=13 March 2011 |newspaper=[[World Nuclear News]] |date=11 March 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5xrvetgTI?url=http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/RS_Massive_earthquake_hits_Japan_1103111.html |archivedate=11 April 2011 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }};</ref> At 05:30 JST, it had reached 820 [[Pascal (unit)|kPa]], 2.1 times normal.<ref name="WNN1"/> After isolation cooling had ceased to operate, TEPCO started relieving pressure and injecting water.<ref name="TEPCO12-3:11">{{cite press release|url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11031217-e.html |title=Press Release &#124; Plant status of Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Station (as of 11&nbsp;am March&nbsp;12th&nbsp;) |work=TEPCO |date=12 March 2011 |accessdate=23 March 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ya4IHeQs?url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11031217-e.html |archivedate=10 May 2011 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref> One employee working inside Unit 1 at this time received a radiation dose of 106 mSv and was later sent to a hospital to have his condition assessed.<ref name="TEPCO12-3:13">{{cite press release |url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11031219-e.html |title=Press Release &#124; Plant Status of Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Station (as of 1&nbsp;pm 12 March) |work=TEPCO |date=12 March 2011 |accessdate=23 March 2011| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140328143040/http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11031219-e.html | archivedate = 2014-03-28| deadurl=no}}</ref>

Without electricity, needed for water pumps and ventilation fans, ising heat within the containment area led to increasing pressure.<ref>[http://allthingsnuclear.org/post/3792741638/containment-at-fukushima Containment at Fukushima]. All Things Nuclear. Retrieved 12 March 2011. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120515195631/http://allthingsnuclear.org/post/3792741638/containment-at-fukushima |date=15 May 2012 }}</ref><ref name="nytimesWilson">David Sanger and Matthew Wald, [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/14/world/asia/japan-fukushima-nuclear-reactor.html Radioactive releases in Japan could last months, experts say.] ''The New York Times'' 13 March 2011 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925004946/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/14/world/asia/japan-fukushima-nuclear-reactor.html |date=25 September 2012 }}</ref> In a press release on 12 March at 07:00 JST, TEPCO stated, "Measurement of radioactive material ([[iodine-131]], etc.) by monitoring car indicates increasing value compared to normal level. One of the monitoring posts is also indicating higher than normal level."<ref name="TEPCO-7AM">{{cite press release |url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11031211-e.html |title=Impact to TEPCO's Facilities due to Miyagiken-Oki Earthquake (as of 7&nbsp;am) |work=TEPCO News website |date=12 March 2011 |accessdate=12 March 2011| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131112160639/http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11031211-e.html | archivedate = 2013-11-12| deadurl=no}}</ref> Dose rates recorded on the main gate rose from 69 [[nano-|n]][[Gray (unit)|Gy]]/h (for [[gamma ray|gamma]] radiation, equivalent to 69 n[[sievert|Sv]]/h) at 04:00 JST, 12 March, to 866 nGy/h 40&nbsp;minutes later, before hitting a peak of 0.3855 mSv/h at 10:30 JST.<ref name="TEPCO-7AM"/><ref>Nikkei, [https://web.archive.org/web/20110720010422/http://e.nikkei.com/e/fr/tnks/Nni20110312D12JF363.htm Radiation could already have leaked at nuke plant.]. 12 March 2011, 7:20 JST.</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/cc/press/betu11_j/images/110312g.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722100148/http://www.tepco.co.jp/cc/press/betu11_j/images/110312g.pdf|archivedate=2011-07-22|script-title=ja:福島第一原子力発電所モニタリングカーによる計測状況|accessdate=13 March 2011|work=TEPCO|language=Japanese|quote=69 nGy/h ... 866 nGy/h ... 385.5 μSv/h}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/cc/press/11031226-j.html|script-title=ja:福島第一原子力発電所の現状について【午後４時40分時点】|trans-title=Condition of Fukushima I (16:40)|date=12 March 2011|accessdate=12 March 2011|work=TEPCO|language=Japanese| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131014110636/http://www.tepco.co.jp/cc/press/11031226-j.html | archivedate = 2013-10-14| deadurl=no}}</ref> At 13:30 JST, workers detected radioactive [[caesium-137]] and [[iodine-131]] near Reactor 1, a sign that water levels in the coolant system had dropped so low that some of the core's [[Behavior of nuclear fuel during a reactor accident#Cracking and overheating of the fuel|fuel had melted]], after being exposed to the air.<ref name="IAEAtsunami1"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://e.nikkei.com/e/fr/tnks/Nni20110312D12JF423.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615091642/http://e.nikkei.com/e/fr/tnks/Nni20110312D12JF423.htm|archivedate=2011-06-15|title=Possible Meltdown at TEPCO Reactor|work=Nikkei.com|date=12 March 2011}}</ref> Cooling water levels had fallen so much that parts of the [[Nuclear fuel|nuclear fuel rods]] were exposed and partial melting might have occurred.<ref>{{cite web|author=Yoshie Furuhashi |url=http://mrzine.monthlyreview.org/2011/nhk110311.html |title=NHK, "Fukushima 1: Fuel Rods Exposed" |work=Mrzine.monthlyreview.org |date=12 March 2011 |quote=As of 11:20, a part of the "fuel assembly" of fuel rods is now exposed above water. |accessdate=13 March 2011| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120905020302/http://mrzine.monthlyreview.org/2011/nhk110311.html | archivedate = 2012-09-05| deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="mccurry13">{{cite news|author=McCurry, Justin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/mar/13/japan-second-nuclear-reactor-threat-fukushima |title=Japan nuclear plant faces new threat|work=The Guardian |date=13 March 2011 |accessdate=13 March 2011 |place=London| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130601020333/http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2011/mar/13/japan-second-nuclear-reactor-threat-fukushima | archivedate = 2013-06-01| deadurl=no}}</ref> Radiation levels at the site boundary exceeded the regulatory limits.<ref name="TEPCO-boundary-radiation">{{cite press release|url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11031224-e.html |title=TEPCO press release 4 |author=Tepco |work=TEPCO News website |date=12 March 2011 |accessdate=12 March 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5y9vdvlgf?url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11031224-e.html |archivedate=23 April 2011 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref>

On 14 March, radiation levels had continued to increase on the premises, measuring at 02:20 an intensity of 0.751 mSv/h on one location and at 02:40 an intensity of 0.650 mSv/h at another location on the premises.<ref name="kyodonews-radiation">{{cite news|author=Kyodo|url=http://english.kyodonews.jp/news/2011/03/77515.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110513050653/http://english.kyodonews.jp/news/2011/03/77515.html|archivedate=2011-05-13|title=Radiation level again tops legal limit at Fukushima No. 1 nuke plant|agency=Kyodo News |date=14 March 2011 |accessdate=14 March 2011}}</ref> On 16 March, the maximum readings peaked at 10.850 mSv/h.<ref name="TEPCO-boundary-radiation-2">{{cite press release|url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11031224-e.html |title=TEPCO press release 4 |author=Tepco |work=TEPCO News website |date=12 March 2011 |accessdate=17 March 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5y9vdvlgf?url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11031224-e.html |archivedate=23 April 2011 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref>

===Hydrogen explosion===
At 07:00 JST on 12 March, Prime Minister Naoto Kan asked Daiichi director [[Masao Yoshida (nuclear engineer)|Masao Yoshida]] why his workers were not opening the valves to release rising steam pressure within the reactor. Yoshida answered that they could not open the electrical valves because of the power failure and the radiation was too high to send workers to manually open the valves. Nevertheless, with the pressure and temperatures continuing to rise, at 09:15, TEPCO sent workers to begin manually opening the valves. The high radiation slowed the work and the valves were not opened until 14:30.<ref>Yoshida, Reiji, "[http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20110607a3.html Probe poised to take Tepco to task]", ''Japan Times'', 7 June 2011, p. 1. {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>

At 15:36 JST on 12 March, there was an explosion in the reactor building at Unit 1. The side walls of the upper level were blown away, leaving in place only the vertical steel framed gridworks. The roof collapsed, covering the floor and some machinery on the south side. The walls were relatively intact compared to later explosions at Units 3 and 4.<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ja:福島第１原発で爆発と白煙　４人ケガ|url=http://www.news24.jp/articles/2011/03/12/06178055.html|work=Nippon Television Network Corporation|accessdate=12 March 2011|language=Japanese| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130714031352/http://www.news24.jp/articles/2011/03/12/06178055.html | archivedate = 2013-07-14| deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11031234-e.html|title=TEPCO press release 34|work=Tepco|date=12 March 2011| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130317234851/http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11031234-e.html | archivedate = 2013-03-17| deadurl=no}}</ref> Video of the explosion shows that it was primarily directed sideways.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B3_ZRO5oATk&NR=1 Fukushima (Japan) Nuclear Power Plant Explosion 12 March 2011 - YouTube] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110321033158/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B3_ZRO5oATk&NR=1 |date=21 March 2011 }}</ref>

The roof of the building was designed to provide ordinary weather protection for the areas inside, not to withstand the high pressure of an explosion. In the Fukushima I reactors the primary containment consists of "drywell" and "wetwell" concrete structures below the top level, immediately surrounding the reactor pressure vessel. The secondary containment includes the top floor with water-filled pools for storing fresh or irradiated fuel and for storage of irradiated tools and structures.<ref name=WNN1/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://allthingsnuclear.org/post/3824043948/update-on-fukushima-reactor |work=allthingsnuclear.org |title=Drawing of the reactor and explanation of the containments |accessdate=13 March 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5xA5UxurO?url=http://allthingsnuclear.org/post/3824043948/update-on-fukushima-reactor |archivedate=13 March 2011 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref>

Experts soon agreed that the cause was a hydrogen explosion.<ref name="ReutersSeaWater">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/12/japan-quake-reactor-idUSTKZ00680620110312 |title=Japan to fill leaking nuke reactor with sea water|date=12 March 2011|work=Reuters|author=Kihara, Leika| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140213234715/https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/12/japan-quake-reactor-idUSTKZ00680620110312 | archivedate = 2014-02-13| deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="reuters-20110312-10:37">{{cite news |url=https://af.reuters.com/article/energyOilNews/idAFLDE72B05X20110312|title=Hydrogen may have caused Japan atom blast-industry|author=Fredrik Dahl, Louise Ireland|work=Reuters |date=12 March 2011 |accessdate=12 March 2011| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121021212958/https://af.reuters.com/article/energyOilNews/idAFLDE72B05X20110312 | archivedate = 2012-10-21| deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://e.nikkei.com/e/fr/tnks/Nni20110312D12JFF03.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720010322/http://e.nikkei.com/e/fr/tnks/Nni20110312D12JFF03.htm|archivedate=2011-07-20|title=2011/03/13 01:04 – Meltdown caused nuke plant explosion: Safety body |work=E.nikkei.com |accessdate=13 March 2011}}</ref> Almost certainly the hydrogen was formed inside the reactor vessel<ref name="ReutersSeaWater"/> because of falling water levels exposing [[zircaloy]] structures/fuel assembly cladding, which then reacted with steam and produced hydrogen,<ref>{{cite book|title=Nuclear fuel behaviour in loss-of-coolant accident (LOCA) conditions|year=2009|work=Nuclear Energy Agency, OECD|isbn=978-92-64-99091-3|page=140|url=https://www.oecd-nea.org/nsd/reports/2009/nea6846_LOCA.pdf}}</ref> with the hydrogen subsequently vented into the containment building.<ref name=ReutersSeaWater/> When the hydrogen reached ignition concentration in the air of the secondary containment building, an ignition source such as a spark triggered a hydrogen-oxygen explosion, blowing out the walls of this building from the inside.

Officials indicated that reactor primary containment (the reactor pressure vessel) had remained intact and that there had been no large leaks of radioactive material,<ref name=WNN1/><ref name=ReutersSeaWater/> although an increase in radiation levels was confirmed following the explosion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://finchannel.com/news_flash/World/82983_Radiation_levels_increase_at_Fukushima_No.1_after_blast_reports/ |title=The Financial – Radiation levels increase at Fukushima No.1 after blast reports |work=Finchannel.com |accessdate=12 March 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120807075325/http://finchannel.com/news_flash/World/82983_Radiation_levels_increase_at_Fukushima_No.1_after_blast_reports/# |archivedate=7 August 2012 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Meyers, Chris |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/12/us-japan-quake-idUSTRE72A0SS20110312 |title=Radiation leaking from Japan's quake-hit nuclear |work=Reuters |date=9 February 2009 |accessdate=12 March 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5x8161jJj?url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/12/us-japan-quake-idUSTRE72A0SS20110312 |archivedate=12 March 2011 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref> The report<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kantei.go.jp/foreign/kan/topics/201106/iaea_houkokusho_e.html |title=Report of Japanese Government to the IAEA Ministerial Conference on Nuclear Safety |date=June 2011 |accessdate=9 June 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zQaYiE7t?url=http://www.kantei.go.jp/foreign/kan/topics/201106/iaea_houkokusho_e.html |archivedate=14 June 2011 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref> of the fact-finding commission states that "There is a possibility that the bottom of the RPV [reactor pressure vessel] was damaged and some of the fuel might have dropped and accumulated on the D/W [dry well] floor (lower pedestal)." The Fukushima prefectural government reported radiation dose rates at the plant reaching 1.015 [[Milli-|m]][[sievert|Sv]]/h.<ref name="abc3162450">{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2011/03/12/3162450.htm |title=Explosion at quake-hit nuclear plant |work=ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |date=12 March 2011 |accessdate=12 March 2011| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110707174109/http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2011/03/12/3162450.htm | archivedate = 2011-07-07| deadurl=no}}</ref> The [[IAEA]] stated on 13 March that four workers had been injured by the explosion at the Unit 1 reactor, and that three injuries were reported in other incidents at the site. They also reported one worker was exposed to higher-than-normal radiation levels but the level fell below their guidance for emergency situations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iaea.org/newscenter/news/fukushima-nuclear-accident-update-log-16 |title=IAEA update on Japan earthquake |work=iaea.org |date=2011-03-13 |quote=At Fukushima Daiichi, four workers were injured by the explosion at the Unit 1 reactor, and there are three other reported injuries in other incidents. In addition, one worker was exposed to higher-than-normal radiation levels that fall below the IAEA guidance for emergency situations. |accessdate=2017-08-07 |df=dmy }}</ref>

===Seawater used for cooling===
At 20:05 JST on 12 March, the Japanese government ordered [[seawater]] to be injected into Unit 1 in a new effort to cool the reactor core.<ref name="nisa313">{{cite web|url=http://www.nisa.meti.go.jp/english/files/en20110313-3.pdf |title=Seismic Damage Information(the 19th Release) |date=13 March 2011 |work=[[Nuclear and Industrial Safety Agency]] |accessdate=12 April 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6E0qt3Eii?url=http://www.nisa.meti.go.jp/english/files/en20110313-3.pdf |archivedate=28 January 2013 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy }}</ref> The treatment had been held as a last resort since it ruins the reactor.<ref>[http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/World-News/Video-Japan-Quake-And-Tsunami-Plea-For-US-Help-After-Third-Explosion-At-Nuclear-Plant/Article/201103215951706 SkyNewsHD]. Radiation Leaks After Third Japanese Blast {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110427104348/http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/World-News/Video-Japan-Quake-And-Tsunami-Plea-For-US-Help-After-Third-Explosion-At-Nuclear-Plant/Article/201103215951706 |date=27 April 2011 }}</ref> TEPCO started seawater cooling at 20:20, adding [[boric acid]] as a [[neutron absorber]] to prevent a [[criticality accident]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11031231-e.html|title=mpact to TEPCO's Facilities due to Miyagiken-Oki Earthquake (as of 9PM)|date=12 March 2011|accessdate=12 March 2011|work=TEPCO| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140410163446/http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11031231-e.html | archivedate = 2014-04-10| deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/cc/press/11031229-j.html |script-title=ja:東北地方太平洋沖地震における当社設備への影響について【午後９時現在】 |date=12 March 2011 |accessdate=12 March 2011 |work=TEPCO |language=Japanese |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5x8oLVxOT?url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/cc/press/11031229-j.html |archivedate=13 March 2011 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref> The water would take five to ten hours to fill the reactor core, after which the reactor would cool down in around ten days.<ref name=ReutersSeaWater/> The injection of seawater into the reactor pressure vessel was done by fire department trucks.<ref name="nisa29">{{cite web|url=http://www.nisa.meti.go.jp/english/files/en20110318-2.pdf |title=Seismic Damage Information (the 29th Release) |date=18 March 2011 |work=Nuclear and Industrial Safety Agency |accessdate=12 April 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yWYm8DlQ?url=http://www.nisa.meti.go.jp/english/files/en20110318-2.pdf |archivedate=8 May 2011 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=NISA38/><ref>{{Citation|title = Specials: Japan earthquake and nuclear crisis|url = http://www.nature.com/news/specials/japanquake/index.html|journal = Nature|accessdate = 17 April 2011|deadurl = yes|archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/5xIJYxczV?url=http://www.nature.com/news/specials/japanquake/index.html|archivedate = 19 March 2011|df = dmy-all}}</ref> At 01:10 JST on 14 March, injection of seawater was halted for two hours because all available water in the plant pools had run out (similarly, feed to Unit 3 was halted).<ref name=nisa29/> NISA news reports stated 70% of the fuel rods had been damaged when uncovered.<ref name="latimes671"/>

On 12 March, a new electrical distribution panel was installed in an office adjacent to Unit 1 to supply power via Unit 2 when it was reconnected to the transmission grid two days later.<ref name=NISA38/> On 21 March, injection of seawater continued, as did repairs to the control instrumentation.<ref name=IAEAtsunami1/> On 23 March, it became possible to inject water into the reactor using the feed water system rather than the fire trucks, raising the flow rate from 2 to 18&nbsp;m<sup>3</sup>/h (later reduced to 11m<sup>3</sup>/h,<ref name="TEPCO23-3:23">{{cite press release |url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11032303-e.html |title=Press Release &#124; Plant Status of Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Station (as of 11:00&nbsp;pm 22 Mar) |work=TEPCO |accessdate=26 March 2011| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140215110724/http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11032303-e.html | archivedate = 2014-02-15| deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="NISA46">{{cite web|url=http://www.nisa.meti.go.jp/english/files/en20110323-4-1.pdf |title=Seismic Damage Information (the 46th Release) |date=23 March 2011 |work=Nuclear and Industrial Safety Agency |accessdate=12 April 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5xtNJwUOK?url=http://www.nisa.meti.go.jp/english/files/en20110323-4-1.pdf |archivedate=12 April 2011 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy }}</ref> and even further to reduce the build up of contaminated water); on 24 March, electricity was restored to the central operating room.<ref name="NISA61">{{cite web|url=http://www.nisa.meti.go.jp/english/files/en20110330-1-1.pdf |title=Seismic Damage Information (the 61st Release) |date=29 March 2011 |work=Nuclear and Industrial Safety Agency |accessdate=12 April 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5xs2iKmoX?url=http://www.nisa.meti.go.jp/english/files/en20110330-1-1.pdf |archivedate=11 April 2011 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy }}</ref>

As of 24 March, the spent fuel pool was "thought to be fully or partially exposed", according to CNN.<ref name="cnn-status-0324"/> Pressure in the reactor had increased owing to the seawater injection, resulting in steam being vented, later alleviated by reducing the water flow. Temperature increases were also reportedly temporary. TEPCO condensed some of the steam to water in the spent fuel pool.

It was estimated<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forandagainst.com/Fear_Of_Fukushima_s_Reactors_Cooling_Systems_Clogging_Up_With_Salt |title=Fear Of Fukushima's Reactors Cooling Systems Clogging Up With Salt |work=Forandagainst.com |date=24 March 2011 |accessdate=24 April 2011| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120315235504/http://www.forandagainst.com/Fear_Of_Fukushima_s_Reactors_Cooling_Systems_Clogging_Up_With_Salt | archivedate = 2012-03-15| deadurl=no}}</ref> that as much as 26 tonnes of sea salt may have accumulated in reactor Unit 1 and twice that amount in Units 2 and 3. As salt clogs cooling pipes and erodes zirconium oxide layer of the fuel rods, switching to the use of freshwater for cooling was a high priority.

The use of seawater has the potential to make uranium chemistry more complex; in pure water the [[hydrogen peroxide]] formed by the radiolysis of water can react with uranium dioxide to form a solid peroxide mineral known as [[studtite]]. According to Navrotsky ''et al.'' this mineral has been found in the fuel storage pond at the plutonium production site at [[Hanford Site|Hanford]]. Navrotsky ''et al.'' report that when alkali metal ions are present, uranium can form nanoparticles (U<sub>60</sub> clusters) which may be more mobile than the solid studtite.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Armstrong | first1 = C.R. | last2 = Nyman | first2 = M. | last3 = Shvareva | first3 = T. | last4 = Sigmon | first4 = G.E. | last5 = Burns | first5 = P.C. | last6 = Navrotsky | first6 = A. | year = 2012 | title = Uranyl peroxide enhanced nuclear fuel corrosion in seawater| journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 109 | issue = | pages = 1874–1877 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.1119758109 | pmid=22308442 | pmc=3277545}}</ref> A review of the research done at the University of Notre Dame on the subject of nanoscale actinyl clusters was published in 2010.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Burns | first1 = Peter C. | year = 2010 | title = From extended solids to nano-scale actinide clusters| url = | journal = Comptes Rendus Chimie | volume = 13 | issue = 6–7| pages = 737–746 | doi=10.1016/j.crci.2010.01.014}}</ref>

===Reactor stabilization===
[[File:FukushimaWaterBarge2011.jpg|thumb|Because of saltwater corrosion problems and pipes clogging by salt, fresh cooling water is transported by barge to Fukushima.]]
By 24 March, electrical power (initially from temporary sources, but off-site power used from 3 April) was being restored to parts of the unit, with the Main Control Room lighting being restored.<ref name="7746P"/>

On 25 March, fresh water became available again to be added to the reactor instead of salt water,<ref name="TEPCO25-3:10">{{cite press release |url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11032515-e.html |title=Press Release &#124; Plant status of Fukushima Daiichi nuclear power station (as of 10:30&nbsp;pm 25 Mar) |work=TEPCO |accessdate=26 March 2011| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120723090714/http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11032515-e.html | archivedate = 2012-07-23| deadurl=no}}</ref> while work continued to repair the unit's cooling systems.<ref name="iaea1714">{{cite press release |url=http://www.iaea.org/press/?p=1714 |title=Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Accident Update (25&nbsp;March,&nbsp;05:15 UTC): IAEA Alert Log: Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Accident |work=Iaea.org |accessdate=26 March 2011| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110429052803/http://www.iaea.org/press/?p=1714 | archivedate = 2011-04-29| deadurl=yes}}</ref> A volume of 1890&nbsp;m<sup>3</sup> (500,000 USgal) of fresh water was brought to the plant by a barge provided by the US Navy.<ref name="USNavy25">{{cite web|url=http://www.navy.mil/search/display.asp?story_id=59318 |title=U.S. Navy to provide 500,000 gallons of fresh water to Fukushima power plant |date=25 March 2011 |work=NAVY.mil |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111125120835/http://www.navy.mil/search/display.asp?story_id=59318 |archivedate=25 November 2011 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref> On 29 March, the fire trucks which had been used to inject water into the reactor were replaced by electrical pumps.<ref name=NISA61/>

On 28 March, pumping began to remove water contaminated with radioactive [[Caesium-137|<sup>137</sup>Cs]] and [[Iodine-131|<sup>131</sup>I]] from basement areas, storing it in the condenser system.<ref name=NISA61/> By 29 March, pumping was halted because condensate reservoirs were almost full and plans were being considered to transfer water to the suppression pool surge tanks.<ref name="TEPCO30-3:20">{{cite press release |url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11033015-e.html |title=Press Release &#124; Status of TEPCO's Facilities and its services after the Tohoku-Taiheiyou-Oki Earthquake(as of 10:00&nbsp;pm) |work=TEPCO |date=30 March 2011 |accessdate=7 April 2011| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140401175651/http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11033015-e.html | archivedate = 2014-04-01| deadurl=no}}</ref>

On 7 April, TEPCO began injecting nitrogen into the containment vessel, which was expected to reduce the likelihood of further hydrogen explosions.<ref>[http://canteach.candu.org/library/20044507.pdf Dr. Johanna Daams, Nuclear reactor containment design], Chapter 2: Hydrogen, radionuclides and severe accidents module A: Hydrogen, 2A-4 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111126091001/http://canteach.candu.org/library/20044507.pdf |date=26 November 2011 }}</ref> The injection has been ongoing since then and has been repeated on the other units at Fukushima.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20110407x1.html |title=Tepco pumps nitrogen into Reactor 1 |work=Japan Times |date=7 April 2011 |accessdate=24 April 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5xmd5NA46?url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20110407x1.html |archivedate=8 April 2011 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref> On 7 April, before a large aftershock, temperatures in the reactor core unexpectedly "surged in temperature to 260&nbsp;°C"; the cause was unknown, but the temperature dropped to 246&nbsp;°C by 8 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20110409a2.html |title=Latest jolt tests other nuclear plants, but no leaks |work=Japan Times |date=9 April 2011 |accessdate=24 April 2011}}</ref> On 27 April, TEPCO revised its estimate of damaged fuel in Unit 1 from 55% to 70%.<ref name=n1/>

On 17 April, remote control robot was used to enter the Reactor Building and performed a series of inspections, which confirmed on 29 April that there was no significant water leakage coming from the containment vessel.<ref name=7746P/>

On 23 and 26 April, concerns that Unit 1 fuel rods may be exposed to air caused TEPCO to consider filling the "containment vessel with water to cool the reactor" despite concerns for building integrity.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090529082420/http://www.nhk.or.jp/daily/english/26_31.html TEPCO to fill No.1 reactor with water], NHK, 26 April 2011.</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110522223434/http://www3.nhk.or.jp/daily/english/23_05.html Reactor 1 water level concerns], NHK, 23 April 2011.</ref> Efforts were slowed by Unit 1 radiation measurements "as high as 1,120 millisierverts of radiation per hour".<ref name="bloomberg.com">[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-27/tokyo-water-radiation-falls-to-zero-for-first-time-since-crisis.html Radiation Readings in Fukushima Reactor Rise to Highest Since Crisis Began], Bloomberg, 27 April 2011 {{webarchive |url=https://www.webcitation.org/5yG6JyTQO?url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-27/tokyo-water-radiation-falls-to-zero-for-first-time-since-crisis.html |date=27 April 2011 }}</ref> On 13 May, TEPCO announced it would proceed with a plan to fill the containment vessel despite the possibility of holes caused by melting fuel elements in the pressure vessel.<ref name="bloomberg.com"/><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/05/12/us-japan-nuclear-reactor-idUSTRE74B1H520110512 Fukushima reactor has a hole, leading to leakage], Reuters, 12 May 2011 {{webarchive |url=https://www.webcitation.org/5yd1SrWvn?url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/05/12/us-japan-nuclear-reactor-idUSTRE74B1H520110512 |date=12 May 2011 }}</ref> TEPCO had expected to increase the amount of water pumped to Unit 1 to compensate for any leakage from the holes<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110519022809/http://www3.nhk.or.jp/daily/english/13_03.html No.1 reactor is in a "meltdown" state], NHK, 13 May 2011.</ref> but decided on 15 May to abandon the plan after finding the Unit 1 basement was already half flooded.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-13404548 Japan nuclear: Tepco halts Fukushima cooling plan], BBC, 15 May 2011. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120601023125/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-13404548 |date=1 June 2012 }}</ref>

On 5 May, ventilation systems were installed in the Reactor Building, to clean the highly radioactive air encapsulated in it.<ref name=7746P/>

On 12 May, the water level gauge for the reactor was calibrated, and it was subsequently identified that the water level was lower than previously thought (as the water level went off the lower side of the gauge).<ref name=7746P/>

On 13 May, preparatory work started on the installation of the Reactor Building covers. Construction work started on 28 June.<ref name="110819e2"/>

On 20 May, staff entered the Reactor Building, confirming reactor water level and radioactivity.<ref name=110819e2/>

Since 2 July, the reactor has been cooled using fresh water from the on-site water treatment plant.<ref name=110819e2/>

On 21 August, TEPCO reported that all of the temperature sensors of Unit 1 were recording temperatures less than 100 degrees Celsius on Friday 19 August. Once other goals are met, Unit 1 will have achieved cold shutdown state.<ref name="576P">{{cite web |url= http://www.jaif.or.jp/english/news_images/pdf/ENGNEWS01_1313897576P.pdf |title= Earthquake Report number 180 |work= JAIF |accessdate= 22 August 2011 |deadurl= yes |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20111011132608/http://www.jaif.or.jp/english/news_images/pdf/ENGNEWS01_1313897576P.pdf |archivedate= 11 October 2011 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>

On 28 October, TEPCO reported the completion of cover construction at reactor building of Unit 1 of Fukushima Daiichi nuclear power station.<ref name="TEPCO-COVER">{{cite press release |url= http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11102806-e.html |title= Completion of Cover Construction at Reactor Building of Unit 1 of Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Station |work=TEPCO |accessdate=7 November 2011| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140213190757/http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11102806-e.html | archivedate = 2014-02-13| deadurl=no}}</ref>

On 19 January 2012, the interior of the primary containment vessel of reactor 2 was inspected by TEPCO for the first time after the accident, with an industrial endoscope. With this device photos were taken and the temperature was measured at this spot and from the cooling-water inside, in an attempt to calibrate the existing temperature-measurements that could have an error margin of 20&nbsp;°C (36&nbsp;°F). The procedure lasted 70&nbsp;minutes.<ref>Nikkei (19 January 2012)[http://e.nikkei.com/e/fr/earthquake/nuc/Nni20120119D19JF860.htm TEPCO uses endoscope to look inside crippled Fukushima reactor] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401182334/http://e.nikkei.com/e/fr/earthquake/nuc/Nni20120119D19JF860.htm |date=1 April 2012 }}</ref> The photos showed parts of the walls and pipes inside the containment vessel, but they were unclear and blurred, most likely due to water vapors and the radiation inside. According to TEPCO the photos showed no serious damage. The temperature measured inside was {{convert|44.7|°C|°F}} and did not differ much from the {{convert|42.6|°C|°F}} measured outside the vessel.<ref>NHK-world (19 January 2012) [http://www3.nhk.or.jp/daily/english/20120119_28.html TEPCO fails to clearly see inside damaged reactor]. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119191628/http://www3.nhk.or.jp/daily/english/20120119_28.html |date=19 January 2012 }}</ref>

===Possibility of criticality===
Reports of 13 observations of neutron beams 1.5&nbsp;km "southwest of the plant's No. 1 and 2 reactors" from 13 to 16 March raised the possibility that [[nuclear chain reaction]]s could have occurred after the initial SCRAMing of the reactors at Fukushima Daiichi.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.kyodonews.jp/news/2011/03/80539.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521182726/http://english.kyodonews.jp/news/2011/03/80539.html|archivedate=2011-05-21|title=Neutron beam observed 13 times at crippled Fukushima nuke plant |agency=Kyodo News |accessdate=7 April 2011}}</ref> 16 March reports that fuel rods in the spent fuel pool at Unit 4 could have been exposed to air appeared to indicate that uncontrolled fission may have occurred in that fuel pool.<ref>{{cite news|author=Black, Richard |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-12762608 |title=Surprise 'critical' warning raises nuclear fears |work=BBC Online |date=16 March 2011 |accessdate=7 April 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5xEcKoBfU?url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-12762608 |archivedate=16 March 2011 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref> Later reports of exceptionally high [[iodine-134]] levels appeared to confirm this theory because very high levels of iodine-134 would be indicative of criticality.<ref name="boston.com">{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/news/world/asia/articles/2011/03/28/elevated_radiation_levels_force_plant_evacuation/ |title=Elevated radiation levels force plant evacuation |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |accessdate=12 April 2011 |first1=Hiroko |last1=Tabuchi |first2=Keith |last2=Bradsher |date=28 March 2011| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131101054756/http://www.boston.com/news/world/asia/articles/2011/03/28/elevated_radiation_levels_force_plant_evacuation/ | archivedate = 2013-11-01| deadurl=no}}</ref> The same report also showed high measurements of [[chlorine-38]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nisa.meti.go.jp/english/files/en20110325-6.pdf |title=NISA News Release |format=PDF |accessdate=7 April 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5y2c0NOwW?url=http://www.nisa.meti.go.jp/english/files/en20110325-6.pdf |archivedate=18 April 2011 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy }}</ref> which some nuclear experts used to calculate that self-propagating fission must be occurring in Unit 1.<ref>{{cite news|author=Harrell, Eben |url=http://ecocentric.blogs.time.com/2011/03/30/has-fukushimas-reactor-no-1-gone-critical/ |title=Has Fukushima's Reactor No. 1 Gone Critical? |work=Time |date=30 March 2011 |accessdate=7 April 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5xbIPhI5I?url=http://ecocentric.blogs.time.com/2011/03/30/has-fukushimas-reactor-no-1-gone-critical/ |archivedate=31 March 2011 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lewis.armscontrolwonk.com/files/2011/03/Cause_of_the_high_Cl38_Radioactivity.pdf |title=What was the cause of the high Cl-38 radioactivity in the Fukushima Daiichi Reactor #11 |format=PDF |accessdate=7 April 2011}}</ref> Despite TEPCO suggesting the iodine-134 report was inaccurate, the IAEA appeared to accept the chlorine-based analysis as a valid theory suggesting criticality when it stated at a press conference that "melted fuel in the No. 1 reactor building may be causing isolated, uncontrolled nuclear chain reactions".<ref>{{cite news|author=Tirone, Jonathan |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-30/record-high-levels-of-radiation-found-in-sea-near-crippled-nuclear-reactor.html |title=Japan weighs entombing nuclear plant in bid to halt radiation |work=Bloomberg |accessdate=7 April 2011 |date=31 March 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5xbBONlfA?url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-30/record-high-levels-of-radiation-found-in-sea-near-crippled-nuclear-reactor.html |archivedate=31 March 2011 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref> TEPCO confirmed its concern about the accuracy of the high iodine and chlorine report by formally retracting the report on 21 April,<ref>{{cite news|author=Inajima, Tsuyoshi |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-21/tepco-retracts-chlorine-arsenic-findings-at-fukushima-station.html |title=Tepco Retracts Chlorine, Arsenic Findings at Fukushima Station |work=Bloomberg |date=20 April 2011 |accessdate=24 April 2011| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140407041117/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-21/tepco-retracts-chlorine-arsenic-findings-at-fukushima-station.html | archivedate = 2014-04-07| deadurl=no}}</ref> which eliminated both the exceptionally high iodine-134 and chlorine-38 levels as proof of criticality. TEPCO did not appear to comment on the criticality concern when withdrawing its report,<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11042008-e.html |title=Press Release (April&nbsp;20,&nbsp;2011) Improvement plan for the exact nuclide analysis at the site of Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Station under instruction of NISA |work=Tepco.co.jp |accessdate=24 April 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5y72fwrLa?url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/11042008-e.html |archivedate=21 April 2011 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/press/corp-com/release/betu11_e/images/110420e11.pdf |title=TEPCO Report |format=PDF |accessdate=24 April 2011}}</ref> but the IAEA has not withdrawn its comments, and some off-site experts find the currently measured iodine-134 levels higher than expected.<ref>[http://www.glgroup.com/News/After-5-Halflives-I-131-Higher-than-Cs-134-137-Suggests-Ongoing-Criticalities-53599.html After 5 Halflives, I-131 Higher than Cs-134/137 Suggests Ongoing Criticalities – GLG News]. Glgroup.com (19 April 2011). Retrieved 30 April 2011.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nisa.meti.go.jp/english/files/en20110327-1-5.pdf |title=The result of nuclide analysis in the stagnant water on the basement floor of the turbine building of each unit. |format=PDF |accessdate=7 April 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5xgcAA58q?url=http://www.nisa.meti.go.jp/english/files/en20110327-1-5.pdf |archivedate=4 April 2011 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy }}</ref>

===Meltdown===
On 12 May, TEPCO engineers confirmed that a meltdown occurred, with molten fuel having fallen to the bottom of the reactor's pressure vessel, or RPV.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/japan/8509502/Nuclear-meltdown-at-Fukushima-plant.html |title=Nuclear meltdown at Fukushima plant |date=12 May 2011 |author=Julian Ryall |work=The Daily Telegraph |place=London |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ydGfSyub?url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/japan/8509502/Nuclear-meltdown-at-Fukushima-plant.html |archivedate=12 May 2011 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref> The utility said that fuel rods of the No. 1 reactor are fully exposed, with the water level 1&nbsp;meter (3.3&nbsp;feet) below the base of the fuel assembly. According to a Japanese press report, there are holes in the base of the pressure vessel – these holes were meant for the control-rods. After the fuel had melted, it produced holes in the bottom of the RPV, and then escaped into the containment vessel. In November 2011 TEPCO did not know the shape or porosity of the fuel mass, which is at the bottom of the containment vessel.<ref>TEPCO (30-11-2012)[http://www.tepco.co.jp/en/nu/fukushima-np/images/handouts_111130_04-e.pdf Handout 30 November 2011]</ref> As a result, it is impossible to know exactly how far the fuel mass would have eroded the concrete floor, but TEPCO estimate that no more than 70&nbsp;cm of a 7.6&nbsp;meter concrete slab was eroded away by the hot fuel. The production of heat and steam in unit 1 has decreased, as suggested by both radioactive decay calculations and photographic evidence (same source from TEPCO).

TEPCO estimates the nuclear fuel was exposed to the air less than five hours after the earthquake struck. Fuel rods melted away rapidly as the temperature inside the core reached 2,800&nbsp;°C within six hours. In less than 16&nbsp;hours, the reactor core melted<ref name="Reactor core melted"/> and dropped to the bottom of the pressure vessel, burning a hole through the vessel. By that time, water was pumped into the reactor in an effort to prevent the worst-case scenario – overheating fuel melting its way through the containment and discharging large amounts of radionuclides in the environment.<ref name="WSJCoresDamaged"/> In June the Japanese government confirmed that Unit 1 reactor vessel containment was breached, and pumped cooling water continues to leak months after the disaster.<ref name="ktvz.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.ktvz.com/news/28143212/detail.html |title=Japan: 3 nuclear reactors melted down – News Story – KTVZ Bend |work=Ktvz.com |date=6 June 2011 |accessdate=13 July 2011| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120627071525/http://www.ktvz.com/news/28143212/detail.html | archivedate = 2012-06-27| deadurl=yes}}</ref>

On 11 October 2012, TEPCO released results of the first direct inspections (by remotely operated camera) of conditions in the interior of the Reactor 1 PCV.<ref>[http://ajw.asahi.com/article/0311disaster/fukushima/AJ201210110078 Ashai Shimbun (11/10/2012)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309040356/http://ajw.asahi.com/article/0311disaster/fukushima/AJ201210110078 |date=9 March 2014 }}</ref> These suggest that the initial assumptions concerning the behaviour of the fuel mass during the accident may have been incorrect. In particular, the distribution of radiation levels within the PCV, with peak levels being around the bottom head of the RPV, suggest that the majority of the fuel has in fact been retained within the RPV. Radiation levels are also notably lower around the lower parts of the "Drywell", suggesting that fuel had not reached the bottom of the containment vessel, or damaged the concrete floor slab. There is a further issue in that radiation levels within the water inside the containment are markedly higher than those in the reactor basements, suggesting that either there is limited flow from the PCV to the basement, or that substantial dilution is taking place - raising the issue of what is the flow path for the water.

===Spent fuel pool of reactor 1===
From 31 March, additional sea water was added to the spent fuel pool, initially by using a concrete pump. Fresh water was used from 14 May. By 29 May water was able to be injected using a temporary pump and the Spent Fuel Pool Cooling (FPC) line.<ref name=7746P/><ref name=110819e2/>

On 10 August, the spent fuel pool was switched from the water-injection system – that functioned some 5 months – to a circulatory cooling system. For the first time since the 11 March disaster, all four damaged reactors at the plant were using circulatory cooling systems with heat-exchangers.<ref>''Jaif'' (11 August 2011)[http://www.jaif.or.jp/english/news_images/pdf/ENGNEWS01_1313037997P.pdf Circulatory cooling begins at No.1 reactor pool] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/60vpoDAu2?url=http://www.jaif.or.jp/english/news_images/pdf/ENGNEWS01_1313037997P.pdf |date=14 August 2011 }}</ref>

