{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}} {{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}} {{Infobox person | name = Champa Devi Shukla | image = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Bhopal]], India | death_date = | death_place = | monuments = | residence = | nationality = Indian | other_names = | education = | alma_mater = | occupation = | years_active = | employer = | organization = | agent = | known_for = | notable_works = | style = | influences = | influenced = | home_town = | television = | religion = | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents = | relatives = | awards = [[Goldman Environmental Prize]] (2004) }}
'''Champa Devi Shukla''' is an Indian activist from [[Bhopal]]. She was awarded the [[Goldman Environmental Prize]] in 2004, together with [[Rashida Bee]]. Shukla and Bee have struggled for justice for those who survived the 1984 [[Bhopal disaster]], when 20,000 people were killed, and organized campaigns and trials against the responsible company and its owners.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldmanprize.org/recipient/rashida-bee-champa-devi-shukla/|title=Rashida Bee & Champa Devi Shukla|publisher=Goldman Environmental Foundation|accessdate=10 April 2017}}</ref>
== Bhopal Gas Tragedy == Champa Devi Shukla, along with [[Rashida Bee]], led an international campaign seeking justice for the survivors of the [[Bhopal disaster|1984 Union Carbide Gas Tragedy]] in [[Bhopal]]. Starting with protests and rallies in India, Shukla took her fight against Union Carbide Company (UCC) and its partner, Dow Chemicals, to the streets of New York and other American cities. Dow Chemicals is today fighting a series of cases filed by Champa and other protesters.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://wikipeacewomen.org/wpworg/en/?page_id=2494|title=Champa Devi Shukla (India) {{!}} WikiPeaceWomen – English|website=wikipeacewomen.org|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-12-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://in.reuters.com/article/india-bhopal-anniversary/in-bhopal-two-women-spark-hope-for-disasters-disabled-children-idINKCN0JG0NV20141202|title=In Bhopal, two women spark hope for disaster's disabled children|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|work=IN|access-date=2017-12-23|language=en-IN}}</ref> In 2002, they organised a 19-day hunger strike in [[New Delhi]], demanding that the former Union Carbide CEO Warren Anderson face a criminal trial in [[Bhopal]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://grist.org/article/nijhuis-bee/|title=Rashida Bee of Bhopal, India, fights against the company that devastated her community|date=2004-04-20|work=Grist|access-date=2017-12-23|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greenpeace.org/india/en/Multimedia2/Photos/champa-devi-shukla-goldman-aw/|title=Champa Devi Shukla, Goldman Award Winner and activist from Bhopal, stands vigil at India Gate, New Delhi on the 20th anniversary of the Bhopal Gas Disaster.|work=Greenpeace India|access-date=2017-12-23|language=en-IN}}</ref>
== Awards == Shukla, along with [[Rashida Bee|Bee]], was awarded the 2004 Goldman Environmental Prize for bringing the Bhopal disaster to the international center stage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.goldmanprize.org/recipient/rashida-bee-champa-devi-shukla/|title=Rashida Bee & Champa Devi Shukla - Goldman Environmental Foundation|work=Goldman Environmental Foundation|access-date=2017-12-23|language=en-US}}</ref>
== Personal life == Shukla works at the Central Government Press, where she is a junior binder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/Home-Page/NF2hSpGZJ5HWUVY1nsrRsK/Their-story-is-the-story-of-Bhopal.html|title=Their story is the story of Bhopal - Livemint|website=www.livemint.com|access-date=2017-12-23}}</ref> She was married to a government employee who was killed by cancer in 1997. Two of Shukla's sons also died due to health problems as a result of the methyl isocyanate gas leak. Three other children are still alive, but none lead a normal life.<ref name=":0" />
