{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}} {{Infobox artist | name = Michiko Ishimure |native_name = 石牟礼道子 | birth_date = 11 March 1927 | birth_place = [[Kawaura, Kumamoto|Kawaura]], [[Kumamoto Prefecture]], Japan | death_date = 10 February 2018 | death_place = [[Kumamoto]], [[Kumamoto Prefecture]], Japan | nationality = Japanese | field = writer, activist, environmentalist, writing | works = ''Paradise in the Sea of Sorrow: Our Minamata Disease'', ''Story of the Sea of Camellias'', ''Lake of Heaven'' }}
{{nihongo|'''Michiko Ishimure'''|石牟礼道子|''Ishimure Michiko''|11 March 1927 – 10 February 2018}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chunichi.co.jp/article/front/list/CK2018021002000262.html|title=石牟礼道子さん死去 ９０歳、水俣病告発「苦海浄土」}}</ref> was a Japanese writer and activist.
She won the 1973 [[Ramon Magsaysay Award]], Asia's highest award, for publicizing writings about [[Minamata disease]], which was extremely controversial at the time.<ref>[http://www.rmaf.org.ph/Awardees/Citation/CitationIshimureMic.htm CITATION for Michiko Ishimure], [[Ramon Magsaysay Award]]. Retrieved 10 February 2018.</ref>
==Works== * ''Paradise in the Sea of Sorrow: Our Minamata Disease'' (1969) English translation 2003, Centre for Japanese Studies, University of Michigan. German translation, Livia Monnet: Paradies im Meer des Leidens: die Minamata-Krankheit im Werk der Schriftstellerin Ishimure Michiko (1988, Institut für Japanologie der Universität Wien) * ''Story of the Sea of Camellias'' (1976) * ''Lake of Heaven'' (2008) * ''Anima no tori (Birds of Spirit)'' (1999) * Noh play ''Shiranui'' (2004, trans. 2016)<ref>https://apjjf.org/2016/13/Thornber.html</ref>
